Men are both the largest sector in Toronto’s shelter system and the most frequently affected by occupancy spikes. Across 2021–present, 279 of the 920 total sector spike days occurred in the Men’s sector — 30%, more than any other sector by a significant margin. And unlike other sectors, Men’s spike days skew toward the most severe band: 170 of the 279 crossed the 3 MAD-SD threshold, compared to just 109 at the 2 MAD-SD level, indicating that Men’s sector anomalies tend to be pronounced rather than subtle. This is consistent with a broader pattern in Toronto’s homelessness data: men make up the majority of the city’s chronically homeless population. When the system comes under pressure, the Men’s sector shows it first and most sharply. That pattern is visible here.

